How Networking Protocols Work Together (Cybersecurity View)\par
\par
When you open a website, many protocols work together in layers.\par
\par
Example:\par
You type google.com in your browser.\par
\par
The process happens like this:\par
\par
User\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f0\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f3  \f0 1. DNS Request\par
\f3  \f1\u9660?\f0\par
DNS Server\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f0\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f3  \f0 Returns IP address\par
\f3  \f1\u9660?\f0\par
Web Server\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f0\par
\f3  \f1\u9474?\f3  \f0 Data sent using HTTP/HTTPS\par
\f3  \f1\u9660?\f0\par
Your Browser\par
\par
But in reality, it is more complex. Let\f3\rquote\f0 s break it down.\par
\par
Step-by-Step Protocol Communication\par
1\u-497?\f1\u8419?\f0  DNS Resolution\par
\par
You type:\par
\par
www.google.com\par
\par
Your computer asks a DNS server:\par
\par
\f3\ldblquote\f0 What is the IP address of google.com?\f3\rdblquote\f0\par
\par
DNS replies:\par
\par
142.250.190.78\par
\par
Now your computer knows where to send the request.\par
\par
Security Risk:\par
\par
DNS spoofing\par
\par
DNS poisoning\par
\par
2\u-497?\f1\u8419?\f0  ARP Request (Local Network)\par
\par
Before sending data, your computer must know the MAC address of the router.\par
\par
So it sends:\par
\par
ARP Request \f2\u8594?\f3  \f0 Who has 192.168.1.1?\par
\par
Router responds with its MAC address.\par
\par
Security Risk:\par
\par
ARP Spoofing\par
\par
Man-in-the-Middle attack\par
\par
3\u-497?\f1\u8419?\f0  TCP Connection\par
\par
Your computer now establishes a connection using TCP.\par
\par
This happens through the 3-way handshake:\par
\par
Client \f2\u8594?\f3  \f0 SYN\par
Server \f2\u8594?\f3  \f0 SYN-ACK\par
Client \f2\u8594?\f3  \f0 ACK\par
\par
This creates a reliable connection.\par
\par
Security Risk:\par
\par
SYN Flood Attack\par
\par
4\u-497?\f1\u8419?\f0  TLS Encryption (for HTTPS)\par
\par
If the site uses HTTPS, the browser starts TLS encryption.\par
\par
Steps:\par
\par
Client Hello\par
Server Hello\par
Key Exchange\par
Secure Channel Established\par
\par
Now the communication becomes encrypted.\par
\par
Security Benefit:\par
\par
Protects passwords\par
\par
Prevents packet sniffing\par
\par
5\u-497?\f1\u8419?\f0  HTTP/HTTPS Request\par
\par
Your browser sends a request:\par
\par
GET /index.html HTTP/1.1\par
\par
The server responds with:\par
\par
HTML\par
Images\par
Scripts\par
Data\par
\par
Security Risks:\par
\par
Session hijacking\par
\par
Cross-site attacks\par
\par
Data interception (if HTTP)\par
\par
